From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: ci <ci@local>
Date: Mon, 25 May 2026 04:30:00 +0000
Subject: patches/0062-fman-pcd-drop-bogus-muram-reservation.patch

PR14z21: skip the bogus 64 KiB pre-reservation that starves PCD allocs.

fman_pcd_muram_alloc() (the sub-allocator used by every CC/KG/manip/PLCR
create) calls fman_muram_alloc() on the GLOBAL muram pool — it does NOT
sub-allocate from the pcd->muram_offset chunk reserved at init.  The
reserved 64 KiB was therefore permanently held hostage, starving the
exact allocations the reservation was supposed to protect.

Empirical proof on LS1046A 2026-05-25 (kernel 6.18.31-vyos): with the
reservation active, after the pre-netdev hook installs 5-port CC
pipelines the global pool has ~1.5 KiB free; every
fman_pcd_manip_chain_create() in the per-flow insert path returns
-ENOMEM on the chain HMTD+HMCT pair while the 3 prior per-manip allocs
succeed.  M2 gate stuck at 6.932 Gbps / 23.25 %% CPU.

Skipping the alloc returns the full ~64 KiB to the global pool for the
same PCD subsystem to consume on demand.  pcd->muram_reserved is kept
for debugfs accounting display; pcd->muram_offset is parked at a
sentinel (-EINVAL) so the release path's IS_ERR_VALUE() guard skips
fman_muram_free.  The err_free: label becomes unreachable and is
removed to silence -Wunused-label.

---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_pcd.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/fman/fman_pcd.c
@@ -533,15 +533,30 @@
 	INIT_LIST_HEAD(&pcd->replic_groups);
 	INIT_LIST_HEAD(&pcd->pending_ports);
 
-	pcd->muram_offset = fman_muram_alloc(muram,
-				     FMAN_PCD_MURAM_RESERVED_BYTES);
-	if (IS_ERR_VALUE(pcd->muram_offset)) {
-		err = (int)pcd->muram_offset;
-		dev_err(fman_get_dev(fman),
-			"fman_pcd: cannot reserve %u bytes MURAM (err %d)\n",
-			FMAN_PCD_MURAM_RESERVED_BYTES, err);
-		goto err_free;
-	}
+	/*
+	 * v1.3 Phase 5 (PR14z21, 2026-05-25): the pre-reservation here
+	 * was a bug.  fman_pcd_muram_alloc() (the sub-allocator used by
+	 * every CC/KG/manip/PLCR create) calls fman_muram_alloc() on
+	 * the GLOBAL muram pool -- it does NOT sub-allocate from this
+	 * pre-reserved chunk.  The reserved bytes were therefore
+	 * permanently held hostage, starving the exact allocations the
+	 * reservation was supposed to protect.
+	 *
+	 * Empirical proof on LS1046A 2026-05-25 (kernel 6.18.31-vyos):
+	 * with the 64 KiB reservation active, after the pre-netdev hook
+	 * installs 5-port CC pipelines the global pool has ~1.5 KiB
+	 * free; every fman_pcd_manip_chain_create() in the per-flow
+	 * insert path returns -ENOMEM on the chain HMTD+HMCT pair while
+	 * the 3 prior per-manip allocs succeed.  M2 gate stuck at
+	 * 6.932 Gbps / 23.25 %% CPU because every HW insert hard-fails.
+	 *
+	 * Skipping the alloc returns the full ~64 KiB to the global
+	 * pool for the same PCD subsystem to consume on demand.  The
+	 * pcd->muram_reserved field is kept for debugfs accounting
+	 * display; pcd->muram_offset is parked at a sentinel so the
+	 * release path's IS_ERR_VALUE() check skips fman_muram_free.
+	 */
+	pcd->muram_offset = (unsigned long)-EINVAL;
 
 	err = fman_pcd_debugfs_root_get();
 	if (err) {
@@ -567,11 +582,6 @@
 		 pcd->muram_offset);
 
 	return pcd;
-
-err_free:
-	mutex_destroy(&pcd->lock);
-	kfree(pcd);
-	return ERR_PTR(err);
 }
 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(fman_pcd_init);
 

